---
title: Winter-Warming Sea Bass with Tapas-Style Potatoes and Charred Peppers
description: During the festive season, fish is often a welcome respite and this recipe is exactly that. Sea bass is beautiful paired with light and zesty flavours like lemon and fresh parsley. Chef Mimi has incorporated some classic Spanish flavours with the patatas bravas for a Christmas dish with a twist!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/lemony-sea-bass-6500e31b-f342b5f0.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/lemony-sea-bass-5dcd4bfaa227e21b8f27874c-e29644b9.pdf
servings: 2
cuisine: Spanish
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/lemony-sea-bass-5dcd4bfaa227e21b8f27874c
time required: 40 minutes
nutrition:
  calories: 762 kcal
  fat: 41 g
  saturated fat: 8 g
  carbohydrates: 61 g
  sugar: 19 g
  protein: 37 g
  sodium: 3 g
  serving size: 792
course: main course
author: Mimi Morley
---

Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Halve, peel and thinly slice the @Echalion shallot{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @yellow pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Zest the @lemon{1}, then cut 3 thin slices per person. Chop the rest into wedges.

Pop the potatoes on a #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with oil, a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Sprinkle over the @paprika{1} and toss to coat them in the spice and oil. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}, turn halfway. Put the lemon zest in a large #bowl{} with the @olive oil{1.5%tbsp}, a pinch of salt and pepper and half the parsley. Add the @sea bass fillets{2} to the bowl, coat in the mixture.

Lay the fish skin side up on a baking tray lined with #baking paper{}. Pop three slices of lemon on the skin of each fish in a single layer. Leave to the side, wash your hands.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the @chorizo{60%g}, stir fry until starting to brown, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the shallot, stir fry until soft, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}, then carefully pour in the @tomato passata{1%pot}.

Pour the @water{50%ml} into the pan. Add a pinch of @salt{pinch}, @black pepper{pinch} and @sugar{pinch}, stir together then simmer the sauce until reduced, ~{4-5%minutes}. Once cooked, taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it, then remove the sauce to a bowl and cover with #foil{}. Wash your pan and pop back on high heat with a drizzle of oil.

At this point you can pop your fish into the oven to bake on the middle shelf for ~{10%minutes}.

Once the pan is hot, add the pepper and fry until nice and charred, ~{5%minutes}. Only stir twice in this time. Once charred, add the @honey{15%g}, @white wine vinegar{12%ml} and @water{} to the pan along with a pinch of salt and pepper. Reduce the heat to medium and cook until the pepper is really soft, ~{5-6%minutes}. Stirring occasionally.

Stir the @baby spinach{250%g} into the pepper in handfuls until wilted.

Once the fish is cooked, transfer to #plates{} and cover with foil if everything else isn't quite ready.

> The fish is cooked when opaque all the way through.

Serve the peppers and spinach alongside. Add the potatoes and then spoon the bravas sauce over the top of the potatoes. Top with a spoonful of @garlic mayonnaise{4%tsp}, serve with a sprinkling of remaining parsley and a lemon wedge. Enjoy!